A key difference between web typography and print is that web type sits vertically centered within it's line-height and knows nothing about it's baseline, x-height, cap-height, or any of those other features.

## Introducing two new ideas

* Vertical Rhythm

* Baseline


## Vertical Rhythm

  Vertical rhythm, in simplest terms, concerns the structural height and spacing of vertically stacked elements, perhaps most commonly the padding, margins and line height. Just like a horizontal grid achieves harmony by restricting the layout to a set of predefined unit sizes, the vertical rhythm (or grid, if you like) solidifies the structure by offering consistent, predictable measures as the user scrolls down the content.

*[Espen Brunborg, Smashing Magazine](https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/12/css-baseline-the-good-the-bad-and-the-ugly/)*


Here's a cool demo to explain what I mean so far:

https://www.gridlover.net/try


## Implementing a vertical rhythm

* Chose a **base font size** for text. Example: `16px`.

* Use a **ratio** to inform your **base line height**. For example `16px * 1.5 = 24px`

* Use a multiple of the **base line height** for all vertical spacing... line-height, height, margin, padding, offsets. Super easy when using `rem` units. Don't forget to offset any vertical space used by borders.

## This is where things get ugly

We achieve this by offsetting the type manually. Usually this is done by adding `padding-top` until the text sits on an imaginary baseline, then we subtract `margin-bottom` to compensate so that the block of text continues to take up the correct amount of space in our vertical rhythm.


Like this:

![Padding and Margin baseline shifts](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*Bh-p7oqCv1WBXxmje9qRYA.png)

*Reference: [Razvan Onofrei](https://medium.com/@razvanonofrei/aligning-type-to-baseline-the-right-way-using-sass-e258fce47a9b)*

You could alternatively combine padding-bottom with a negative (top) offset.


## A new challenge

Because text sites vertically centered within it's line height, the baseline shift required is different for each `font-size` of a `font-family` and is never consistent between font families.


## Solutions for today


**SASS/SCSS Mixin I found online:** https://vicompany.github.io/vertical-rhythm/ calculates and applies offsets after you tell it the Cap-Height of your font.

![Cap-height reminder](data:image/png;base64,)


**Internally at Dash we use our own vertical rhythm mixin library called [base-base](https://dashmedia.github.io/base-base/).** It's less polished with a steeper learning curve however it includes additional mixins for setting and maintaining a vertical rhythm on other block level elements. Fun if you want to dig through some SASS however most of it was created before the use of `rem` units and `calc()` so it's more complicated than it needs to be in 2018.


## Solutions for tomorrow

**[CSS Inline Layout Module Level 3](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-inline-3/)** is a long way out but would potentially make all the difficult parts trivially easy.
